{"cursor":"2612","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\nThe 'optokinetic reflex' is a combination of a saccade and smooth pursuit eye\nmovements. It is seen when an individual follows a moving object with their\neyes, which then moves out of the field of vision at which point their eye moves\nback to the position it was in when it first saw the object. The reflex develops\nat about 6 months of age.\n\nOptokinetic nystagmus (OKN) is nystagmus that occurs in response to a\nrotation movement. It is present normally. The optokinetic reflex allows the\neye to follow objects in motion when the head remains stationary (e.g.,\nobserving individual telephone poles on the side of the road as one travels\nby them in a car).\n","linknr":180,"url":"Optokinetic_reflex","recorded":1374965410,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Optokinetic_reflex&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Optokinetic_reflex&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wizard%2CReferenceTooltips%2Ccharinsert%2Cteahouse%7Cext.rtlcite%2Cwikihiero%7Cext.uls.nojs%7Cmediawiki.legacy.commonPrint%2Cshared%7Cmw.PopUpMediaTransform%7Cskins.vector&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=site&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=startup&only=scripts&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/geoiplookup","//meta.wikimedia.org","#mw-navigation","#p-search","/wiki/File:Optokinetic_nystagmus.gif","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/b/b6/Optokinetic_nystagmus.gif","/wiki/File:Optokinetic_nystagmus.gif","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.22wmf7/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","/wiki/Saccade","/wiki/Smooth_pursuit","#cite_note-